{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HfLHXEjCJ2kg7bngJ2S8uD","type":"tool_result","content":"{\"body\":\"## Problem Statement\\n\\nWe're days away from going live with paid Pro subscriptions. Two correctness bugs in the Stripe integration will cause real revenue/data issues under load:\\n\\n1. **Webhook events can be silently dropped.** The webhook route inserts into `app.stripe_events` *before* running the handler. If the handler throws (DB blip, email outage, anything), Stripe retries, the duplicate guard short-circuits, and the handler never runs — the user paid in Stripe but our DB and our welcome email never reflect it. The `processed_at` column already exists on the table but defaults to `now()` on insert, which makes it useless for tracking actual processing.\\n2. **`getOrCreateCustomer` can leak duplicate Stripe customers.** Two concurrent calls for the same user (double-click, two tabs) both pass the SELECT, both call `stripe.customers.create()`, and we get two Stripe customer records before any DB constraint can intervene. There is no `UNIQUE(user_id)` constraint on `app.subscriptions` today.\\n\\nSeparately, the SQL layer in this repo is hand-written via the `postgres` tagged-template client. There's no compile-time guarantee that what we type matches what's in the DB; `ON CONFLICT`, `RETURNING`, jsonb casts, and cross-schema joins are all loose strings. The schema lives in a sibling repo (`/Users/cippa/Desktop/fly/pomodoro-preview/locus-api/supabase/migrations/`), and any drift between consumer code here and the schema there is currently invisible until a query fails at runtime.\\n\\nGoing live without addressing both of these means accepting silent revenue/data bugs and continued query drift.\\n\\n## Solution\\n\\nA single piece of work delivered in one PR. Migrate the entire DB layer in this app to Prisma — full kill of the current `postgres` client — using the sibling repo's migrations as the authoritative schema source. Then layer the Stripe correctness fixes on top of the Prisma foundation, plus a small set of polish items.\\n\\n**Phase A — Prisma migration (foundation, lands first inside the PR):**\\n\\n1. Add Prisma. Apply the sibling repo's migrations to a local Postgres, introspect into `prisma/schema.prisma` so the schema mirror matches the source of truth byte-for-byte.\\n2. Configure for Vercel: `DATABASE_URL` points at Supabase's Transaction Pooler (port 6543, `?pgbouncer=true&connection_limit=1`), `DIRECT_URL` points at the direct connection (port 5432) for Prisma CLI use.\\n3. Replace every `getDb()` call site with the Prisma client. Keep the small handful of patterns that don't translate cleanly (the `app.entitlements_v` view and the `auth.users.email` read) on `prisma.$queryRaw`.\\n4. Delete `src/lib/db/client.ts` and remove the `postgres` dependency.\\n5. Delete the renewal-reminders cron entirely (route + tests + email template + Vercel cron config). The feature gets re-added in a future PRD; no need to carry a broken `s.id` query through the migration.\\n\\n**Phase B — Stripe correctness fixes (on top of Prisma):**\\n\\n1. **Webhook idempotency.** Migration in sibling repo: drop the `default now()` on `app.stripe_events.processed_at`. Code: insert event row with `processed_at = NULL`, run the handler, only on success set `processed_at = now()`. Duplicate-guard short-circuits only when `processed_at IS NOT NULL`.\\n2. **`getOrCreateCustomer` race.** Migration in sibling repo: add `UNIQUE(user_id)` to `app.subscriptions`. Code: claim the DB row first via `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (user_id) DO NOTHING RETURNING ...`. Only the winning caller proceeds to `stripe.customers.create()`.\\n3. **`customer_update`** on Checkout Session creation so address/name flow back to the Customer record.\\n4. **Idempotency key** on `stripe.checkout.sessions.create()` to make double-click safe.\\n5. **`invoice.payment_failed` handler** so dunning emails fire at the moment of failure, not just when subscription status flips later.\\n\\n## User Stories\\n\\n1. As a paying customer, I want my payment in Stripe to be reliably reflected in the app, so that I don't have to email support after a successful checkout to get my Pro features unlocked.\\n2. As a paying customer, I want to receive my welcome email exactly once after subscribing, so that I'm not spammed by a retry storm.\\n3. As a paying customer who clicks \\\"Get Pro\\\" twice in quick succession, I want exactly one Stripe customer to exist for my account, so that my future billing history isn't fragmented across two Stripe records.\\n4. As a customer who updates my billing address during Checkout, I want that address reflected on future invoices and in the Customer Portal, so that I don't have to re-enter it.\\n5. As a customer whose card fails on a renewal, I want to be told immediately by email, so that I can update my card before losing access.\\n6. As an operator on call, I want failed webhook deliveries to be safely retried by Stripe and re-processed, so that a transient outage doesn't silently lose subscription state.\\n7. As an operator, I want a single source of truth for \\\"what's the state of this subscription?\\\" — the DB row — and trust that it matches Stripe within seconds of any change.\\n8. As a developer working on the billing surface, I want my DB queries to be type-checked against the live schema, so that schema drift between this app and the sibling `locus-api` repo fails at compile time, not in production.\\n9. As a developer, I want one client for all DB access (no bilingual postgres + Prisma codebase), so that conventions and code review are consistent.\\n10. As a developer, I want the same fast mocked-DB unit tests we have today, just against Prisma instead of `getDb()`, so the migration doesn't regress test runtime or developer ergonomics.\\n11. As a developer, I want to delete unused code (renewal-reminders) rather than carry a known-broken cron through the migration.\\n12. As a developer reviewing this codebase six months from now, I want clean separation between Stripe webhook orchestration and DB persistence, so I can change one without re-reading the other.\\n13. As a developer, I want generated Prisma types to surface schema drift before I deploy, so I never ship a query that compiles locally but errors against the live DB.\\n\\n## Implementation Decisions\\n\\n### Schema mirror & codegen\\n\\n- The authoritative schema is `/Users/cippa/Desktop/fly/pomodoro-preview/locus-api/supabase/migrations/`. Prisma's `prisma/schema.prisma` in this repo is **generated by introspection**, not hand-edited, after applying those migrations to a local Postgres. Re-introspect after every schema change in the sibling repo.\\n- Prisma models the `app` schema only. The `auth` schema is Supabase-managed and stays out of `schema.prisma`. Reads of `auth.users.email` go through `prisma.$queryRaw`.\\n- The `app.entitlements_v` view is read via `prisma.$queryRaw` with a hand-typed return shape (Prisma's view support is fragile and the view is the single source of \\\"is user Pro?\\\", so explicit typing is worth the cost). Not written to.\\n\\n### Connection / pooling\\n\\n- `DATABASE_URL` = Supabase Transaction Pooler (port 6543), with `?pgbouncer=true&connection_limit=1`.\\n- `DIRECT_URL` = direct connection (port 5432), used by Prisma CLI for migrations/introspection.\\n- Both configured under the `datasource db` block of `schema.prisma`.\\n\\n### Modules to extract (deep, testable in isolation)\\n\\nThe handler at `src/lib/stripe/events/handle.ts` currently mixes orchestration (event routing, email sending) with persistence (raw SQL). The migration is the natural moment to extract two deep DB modules whose interfaces are stable and rarely change:\\n\\n- **Subscriptions repository.** Operations: claim-or-fetch by user, attach Stripe customer to claimed row, promote-or-insert from a Stripe `Subscription` payload, update-by-Stripe-subscription-ID, mark-canceled-by-Stripe-subscription-ID. Hides the `ON CONFLICT` logic and the placeholder-promotion mechanics from callers.\\n- **Stripe-events repository.** Operations: record-if-new (returns whether the caller claimed it), mark-processed. Hides the `processed_at` semantics from the webhook route.\\n\\nAfter this extraction, `handle.ts` and the webhook route become thin orchestration. Callers no longer touch SQL.\\n\\n### Migrations required in the sibling repo\\n\\nTwo new SQL migrations in `/Users/cippa/Desktop/fly/pomodoro-preview/locus-api/supabase/migrations/`:\\n\\n1. **Add `UNIQUE(user_id)` to `app.subscriptions`.** Pre-flight: confirm no duplicates (none expected pre-launch).\\n2. **Drop the `default now()` on `app.stripe_events.processed_at`.** Existing rows keep their populated value — treated as \\\"already processed\\\", safe.\\n\\nBoth migrations get applied to local + preview before this PR merges, and to live before the live-mode Stripe webhook endpoint is created.\\n\\n### Webhook idempotency contract (post-fix)\\n\\n- On webhook arrival: insert event row with `processed_at = NULL`, `ON CONFLICT (stripe_event_id) DO NOTHING RETURNING ...`.\\n- If insert claimed the row → run handler → on success update `processed_at = now()` → respond 200. On handler error, leave `processed_at` null, respond 500; Stripe retries; next attempt sees null and re-runs.\\n- If insert didn't claim → look up existing row's `processed_at`. Non-null → respond `{ received: true, duplicate: true }`. Null → another delivery is in-flight; return non-200 so Stripe retries.\\n\\n### Race-free `getOrCreateCustomer` contract (post-fix)\\n\\n- Try to claim: `INSERT ... (user_id, status) VALUES (..., 'incomplete') ON CONFLICT (user_id) DO NOTHING RETURNING ...`.\\n- Winner → call `stripe.customers.create()` → `UPDATE ... SET stripe_customer_id = ... WHERE user_id = ...`.\\n- Loser → re-read the row. If `stripe_customer_id` populated, return. If null (rare race window between winner's insert and update), short retry with backoff then error.\\n\\n### Checkout session changes\\n\\n- Add `customer_update: { address: 'auto', name: 'auto' }` to the session create call.\\n- Pass an `idempotencyKey` derived from `userId + priceId + a coarse time bucket` (e.g., 5-minute window) so two clicks within the bucket get the same session URL.\\n\\n### New webhook event\\n\\n- Subscribe to `invoice.payment_failed` on the live (and test/preview) endpoints. Handler dispatches a \\\"card failed\\\" email and logs. No DB write beyond `stripe_events`.\\n\\n### Renewal-reminders deletion (full)\\n\\nDelete: `src/app/api/cron/renewal-reminders/route.ts` (+ `.test.ts`), `src/emails/RenewalReminderEmail.tsx` (+ `.test.tsx` + snapshot), `src/lib/mail/sendRenewalReminder.tsx`, the `crons` array in `vercel.json`. Leave the `renewal_reminder_sent` column on `app.subscriptions` (sibling repo's call to drop later — harmless for now).\\n\\n### Commit ordering inside the PR\\n\\nSingle PR, but bisectable commits in this order: (1) Prisma scaffolding + introspection, (2) repository modules + `getDb()` call-site replacement, (3) delete postgres client + renewal-reminders, (4) Stripe correctness fixes, (5) Stripe polish items. Each commit type-checks and the test suite passes.\\n\\n## Testing Decisions\\n\\n### What makes a good test here\\n\\nTests assert observable behavior: \\\"given event X, the row in `app.subscriptions` has these fields and exactly one welcome email was dispatched.\\\" Tests do not assert that a specific Prisma method was called with a specific argument shape — that's coupling to implementation. Behavior-level assertions survive future refactors of the repository modules.\\n\\nNote on **types ≠ tests**: Prisma's generated client gives compile-time type safety on query inputs and return shapes, which catches schema/code drift. It does not catch behavior bugs (was the right row updated? was the email sent exactly once? does the race fix actually prevent duplicate Stripe customers?). Tests are still required for behavior.\\n\\n### Strategy\\n\\nMocked unit tests, same speed and pattern as today, just mocking Prisma (or — preferred — mocking the new repository modules) instead of `getDb()`. Prior art: `src/lib/stripe/customer.test.ts`, `src/lib/stripe/events/handle.test.ts`, `src/app/api/stripe/webhook/route.test.ts`. Follow those.\\n\\n### Modules that get tested\\n\\n- **Subscriptions repository** — claim semantics (winner/loser), promote-or-insert correctness, idempotency of repeated calls.\\n- **Stripe-events repository** — record-if-new returns false on duplicates, mark-processed only updates rows where `processed_at IS NULL`.\\n- **Webhook handler** — runs on success, leaves `processed_at` null on handler failure, doesn't double-process on retried delivery.\\n- **Checkout session creation** — passes the right `customer_update` and idempotency key.\\n- **`getOrCreateCustomer`** — winner branch and loser branch both return the same customer ID; Stripe is called exactly once across two concurrent calls.\\n\\n## Out of Scope\\n\\n- Real-DB integration tests (deferred to a follow-up issue).\\n- Restricted API keys (follow-up).\\n- `automatic_tax`, `allow_promotion_codes`, `{CHECKOUT_SESSION_ID}` in `success_url` (nice-to-haves).\\n- Renewal reminders rebuild (deleted in this PRD; rebuilt in a future feature PRD).\\n- Dropping the now-unused `renewal_reminder_sent` column from `app.subscriptions` (sibling repo's call when convenient).\\n- Logic changes to `app.profiles` reads/writes — they're included in the Prisma model but only the SQL strings get replaced, no behavior change.\\n- Connect, Treasury, anything outside the subscription billing path.\\n\\n## Further Notes\\n\\n- **Operational rollout for Phase B**: do not create the live-mode webhook endpoint until both new sibling-repo migrations have been applied to the live DB. Order matters; live webhooks against an un-migrated DB would error.\\n- The Stripe API version pin is now `2026-04-22.dahlia` in `src/lib/stripe/client.ts` (handled in a prior PR). The new live webhook uses `2026-03-25.dahlia` — same codename, shape-compatible.\\n- **Preview testing path**: after the PR is up, the Vercel preview gets the new env vars (`DATABASE_URL` = pooler, `DIRECT_URL` = direct), Prisma generates against the introspected schema, and a Stripe test-mode webhook pointed at the preview URL exercises the full webhook + idempotency + race fixes end-to-end before live cutover.\\n- **Why one PR, not two**: per scoping decision, the Stripe fixes ride the Prisma foundation rather than shipping first. Slowest path to live, cleanest history.\\n\",\"comments\":[{\"id\":\"IC_kwDOR5LoTc8AAAABAqP0-A\",\"author\":{\"login\":\"luiscipparrone1\"},\"authorAssociation\":\"MEMBER\",\"body\":\"## Heads-up — Prisma 7 affects this PRD's Phase A & B specifications\\n\\n#35 (Prisma scaffolding) just landed on `preview`. While doing it I hit several breaking changes in Prisma 7 that ripple into the rest of this PRD's child issues. Flagging here so the spec stays consistent.\\n\\nWe're on **Prisma `7.8.0`** (latest stable). It introduced breaking changes vs Prisma 6 that affect every reference to \\\"the Prisma client\\\" in this PRD.\\n\\n### What changed in Prisma 7\\n\\n1. **`datasource db { url = env(...), directUrl = env(...) }` is gone.** The `url` and `directUrl` fields on the schema's datasource block are no longer supported. Connection URLs live in `prisma.config.ts` for the CLI, and runtime connections require a driver adapter. The acceptance criterion in #35 quoting the old syntax is no longer valid.\\n\\n2. **Runtime client requires a driver adapter.** No more `new PrismaClient()` with env-driven connection. Pattern:\\n    ```ts\\n    import { PrismaPg } from \\\"@prisma/adapter-pg\\\"\\n    import { PrismaClient } from \\\"@prisma/client\\\"\\n\\n    const adapter = new PrismaPg({ connectionString: process.env.DATABASE_URL! })\\n    export const prisma = new PrismaClient({ adapter })\\n    ```\\n   This matters for #38 (DB-layer migration) and the repository modules described in this PRD's \\\"Modules to extract\\\" section — they'll all instantiate via the adapter pattern.\\n\\n3. **`findFirst({ take })` is restricted to `1` or `-1`.** Use `findMany({ take: 0 })` for any \\\"does the connection work\\\" smoke check. Affects how tests in #38 / #39 are written.\\n\\n4. **Multi-file schema (`prisma/schema/` folder) is GA.** Used in #35 to keep Supabase's 480-line `auth` schema mirror separate from our 4 owned models. Re-introspection preserves the layout.\\n\\n### What changed about our schema state\\n\\n5. **`subscriptions` is currently `@@ignore`d in the generated client.** Prisma's introspection auto-marks the model because the table has no primary key / unique constraint. Means: `prisma.subscriptions.*` does not exist until #37 ships the `UNIQUE(user_id)` migration and we re-pull.\\n\\n   **Sequencing implication for #38**: the DB-layer migration cannot replace `getDb()` calls that touch `app.subscriptions` until **after** #37 lands and is re-introspected. Either #37 lands first, or #38's commit ordering (per this PRD) needs an explicit \\\"re-introspect after the migration\\\" step inserted before any subscription-related repository module is wired up.\\n\\n6. **`auth.users` cross-schema FKs require `auth` in `schemas`.** Even though we don't write or read auth models via Prisma, `app.pro_trials → auth.users` (and the FKs from `profiles`, `stripe_events`, `subscriptions`) force `auth` into `schemas = [\\\"app\\\", \\\"auth\\\"]`. Every auth model in `prisma/schema/auth.prisma` carries `@@ignore` so the generated client stays clean. The PRD's \\\"auth schema is Supabase-managed and stays out of `schema.prisma`\\\" is approximately preserved — auth models exist for FK validity but are excluded from the generated client.\\n\\n### ⚠️ Vercel deployment gotcha\\n\\nSupabase's transaction pooler (port `6543`, pgBouncer transaction mode) strips prepared statements, which Prisma's introspection / migrate engine relies on. **`DIRECT_URL` must point at port `5432`** (session pooler, or true direct — Vercel has IPv6 so `db.<ref>.supabase.co:5432` works). If `DIRECT_URL` is set to port `6543` on Vercel, `prisma generate` at build time will hang silently.\\n\\nSame warning posted on the affected child issues.\",\"createdAt\":\"2026-04-28T21:37:18Z\",\"includesCreatedEdit\":false,\"isMinimized\":false,\"minimizedReason\":\"\",\"reactionGroups\":[],\"url\":\"https://github.com/synergyio1/locus-landing-page/issues/34#issuecomment-4339266808\",\"viewerDidAuthor\":true}],\"labels\":[{\"id\":\"LA_kwDOR5LoTc8AAAAChKITNg\",\"name\":\"prisma\",\"description\":\"Prisma migration / DB layer work\",\"color\":\"2D3748\"}],\"number\":34,\"state\":\"OPEN\",\"title\":\"Migrate DB layer to Prisma + ship Stripe pre-launch correctness fixes\"}","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"998550bb-d4bb-414a-8904-b08cbc843847","uuid":"bfef4b91-bb9d-4cb0-b59f-5b9babde38d6","timestamp":"2026-04-28T22:25:28.435Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"{\"body\":\"## Problem Statement\\n\\nWe're days away from going live with paid Pro subscriptions. Two correctness bugs in the Stripe integration will cause real revenue/data issues under load:\\n\\n1. **Webhook events can be silently dropped.** The webhook route inserts into `app.stripe_events` *before* running the handler. If the handler throws (DB blip, email outage, anything), Stripe retries, the duplicate guard short-circuits, and the handler never runs — the user paid in Stripe but our DB and our welcome email never reflect it. The `processed_at` column already exists on the table but defaults to `now()` on insert, which makes it useless for tracking actual processing.\\n2. **`getOrCreateCustomer` can leak duplicate Stripe customers.** Two concurrent calls for the same user (double-click, two tabs) both pass the SELECT, both call `stripe.customers.create()`, and we get two Stripe customer records before any DB constraint can intervene. There is no `UNIQUE(user_id)` constraint on `app.subscriptions` today.\\n\\nSeparately, the SQL layer in this repo is hand-written via the `postgres` tagged-template client. There's no compile-time guarantee that what we type matches what's in the DB; `ON CONFLICT`, `RETURNING`, jsonb casts, and cross-schema joins are all loose strings. The schema lives in a sibling repo (`/Users/cippa/Desktop/fly/pomodoro-preview/locus-api/supabase/migrations/`), and any drift between consumer code here and the schema there is currently invisible until a query fails at runtime.\\n\\nGoing live without addressing both of these means accepting silent revenue/data bugs and continued query drift.\\n\\n## Solution\\n\\nA single piece of work delivered in one PR. Migrate the entire DB layer in this app to Prisma — full kill of the current `postgres` client — using the sibling repo's migrations as the authoritative schema source. Then layer the Stripe correctness fixes on top of the Prisma foundation, plus a small set of polish items.\\n\\n**Phase A — Prisma migration (foundation, lands first inside the PR):**\\n\\n1. Add Prisma. Apply the sibling repo's migrations to a local Postgres, introspect into `prisma/schema.prisma` so the schema mirror matches the source of truth byte-for-byte.\\n2. Configure for Vercel: `DATABASE_URL` points at Supabase's Transaction Pooler (port 6543, `?pgbouncer=true&connection_limit=1`), `DIRECT_URL` points at the direct connection (port 5432) for Prisma CLI use.\\n3. Replace every `getDb()` call site with the Prisma client. Keep the small handful of patterns that don't translate cleanly (the `app.entitlements_v` view and the `auth.users.email` read) on `prisma.$queryRaw`.\\n4. Delete `src/lib/db/client.ts` and remove the `postgres` dependency.\\n5. Delete the renewal-reminders cron entirely (route + tests + email template + Vercel cron config). The feature gets re-added in a future PRD; no need to carry a broken `s.id` query through the migration.\\n\\n**Phase B — Stripe correctness fixes (on top of Prisma):**\\n\\n1. **Webhook idempotency.** Migration in sibling repo: drop the `default now()` on `app.stripe_events.processed_at`. Code: insert event row with `processed_at = NULL`, run the handler, only on success set `processed_at = now()`. Duplicate-guard short-circuits only when `processed_at IS NOT NULL`.\\n2. **`getOrCreateCustomer` race.** Migration in sibling repo: add `UNIQUE(user_id)` to `app.subscriptions`. Code: claim the DB row first via `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (user_id) DO NOTHING RETURNING ...`. Only the winning caller proceeds to `stripe.customers.create()`.\\n3. **`customer_update`** on Checkout Session creation so address/name flow back to the Customer record.\\n4. **Idempotency key** on `stripe.checkout.sessions.create()` to make double-click safe.\\n5. **`invoice.payment_failed` handler** so dunning emails fire at the moment of failure, not just when subscription status flips later.\\n\\n## User Stories\\n\\n1. As a paying customer, I want my payment in Stripe to be reliably reflected in the app, so that I don't have to email support after a successful checkout to get my Pro features unlocked.\\n2. As a paying customer, I want to receive my welcome email exactly once after subscribing, so that I'm not spammed by a retry storm.\\n3. As a paying customer who clicks \\\"Get Pro\\\" twice in quick succession, I want exactly one Stripe customer to exist for my account, so that my future billing history isn't fragmented across two Stripe records.\\n4. As a customer who updates my billing address during Checkout, I want that address reflected on future invoices and in the Customer Portal, so that I don't have to re-enter it.\\n5. As a customer whose card fails on a renewal, I want to be told immediately by email, so that I can update my card before losing access.\\n6. As an operator on call, I want failed webhook deliveries to be safely retried by Stripe and re-processed, so that a transient outage doesn't silently lose subscription state.\\n7. As an operator, I want a single source of truth for \\\"what's the state of this subscription?\\\" — the DB row — and trust that it matches Stripe within seconds of any change.\\n8. As a developer working on the billing surface, I want my DB queries to be type-checked against the live schema, so that schema drift between this app and the sibling `locus-api` repo fails at compile time, not in production.\\n9. As a developer, I want one client for all DB access (no bilingual postgres + Prisma codebase), so that conventions and code review are consistent.\\n10. As a developer, I want the same fast mocked-DB unit tests we have today, just against Prisma instead of `getDb()`, so the migration doesn't regress test runtime or developer ergonomics.\\n11. As a developer, I want to delete unused code (renewal-reminders) rather than carry a known-broken cron through the migration.\\n12. As a developer reviewing this codebase six months from now, I want clean separation between Stripe webhook orchestration and DB persistence, so I can change one without re-reading the other.\\n13. As a developer, I want generated Prisma types to surface schema drift before I deploy, so I never ship a query that compiles locally but errors against the live DB.\\n\\n## Implementation Decisions\\n\\n### Schema mirror & codegen\\n\\n- The authoritative schema is `/Users/cippa/Desktop/fly/pomodoro-preview/locus-api/supabase/migrations/`. Prisma's `prisma/schema.prisma` in this repo is **generated by introspection**, not hand-edited, after applying those migrations to a local Postgres. Re-introspect after every schema change in the sibling repo.\\n- Prisma models the `app` schema only. The `auth` schema is Supabase-managed and stays out of `schema.prisma`. Reads of `auth.users.email` go through `prisma.$queryRaw`.\\n- The `app.entitlements_v` view is read via `prisma.$queryRaw` with a hand-typed return shape (Prisma's view support is fragile and the view is the single source of \\\"is user Pro?\\\", so explicit typing is worth the cost). Not written to.\\n\\n### Connection / pooling\\n\\n- `DATABASE_URL` = Supabase Transaction Pooler (port 6543), with `?pgbouncer=true&connection_limit=1`.\\n- `DIRECT_URL` = direct connection (port 5432), used by Prisma CLI for migrations/introspection.\\n- Both configured under the `datasource db` block of `schema.prisma`.\\n\\n### Modules to extract (deep, testable in isolation)\\n\\nThe handler at `src/lib/stripe/events/handle.ts` currently mixes orchestration (event routing, email sending) with persistence (raw SQL). The migration is the natural moment to extract two deep DB modules whose interfaces are stable and rarely change:\\n\\n- **Subscriptions repository.** Operations: claim-or-fetch by user, attach Stripe customer to claimed row, promote-or-insert from a Stripe `Subscription` payload, update-by-Stripe-subscription-ID, mark-canceled-by-Stripe-subscription-ID. Hides the `ON CONFLICT` logic and the placeholder-promotion mechanics from callers.\\n- **Stripe-events repository.** Operations: record-if-new (returns whether the caller claimed it), mark-processed. Hides the `processed_at` semantics from the webhook route.\\n\\nAfter this extraction, `handle.ts` and the webhook route become thin orchestration. Callers no longer touch SQL.\\n\\n### Migrations required in the sibling repo\\n\\nTwo new SQL migrations in `/Users/cippa/Desktop/fly/pomodoro-preview/locus-api/supabase/migrations/`:\\n\\n1. **Add `UNIQUE(user_id)` to `app.subscriptions`.** Pre-flight: confirm no duplicates (none expected pre-launch).\\n2. **Drop the `default now()` on `app.stripe_events.processed_at`.** Existing rows keep their populated value — treated as \\\"already processed\\\", safe.\\n\\nBoth migrations get applied to local + preview before this PR merges, and to live before the live-mode Stripe webhook endpoint is created.\\n\\n### Webhook idempotency contract (post-fix)\\n\\n- On webhook arrival: insert event row with `processed_at = NULL`, `ON CONFLICT (stripe_event_id) DO NOTHING RETURNING ...`.\\n- If insert claimed the row → run handler → on success update `processed_at = now()` → respond 200. On handler error, leave `processed_at` null, respond 500; Stripe retries; next attempt sees null and re-runs.\\n- If insert didn't claim → look up existing row's `processed_at`. Non-null → respond `{ received: true, duplicate: true }`. Null → another delivery is in-flight; return non-200 so Stripe retries.\\n\\n### Race-free `getOrCreateCustomer` contract (post-fix)\\n\\n- Try to claim: `INSERT ... (user_id, status) VALUES (..., 'incomplete') ON CONFLICT (user_id) DO NOTHING RETURNING ...`.\\n- Winner → call `stripe.customers.create()` → `UPDATE ... SET stripe_customer_id = ... WHERE user_id = ...`.\\n- Loser → re-read the row. If `stripe_customer_id` populated, return. If null (rare race window between winner's insert and update), short retry with backoff then error.\\n\\n### Checkout session changes\\n\\n- Add `customer_update: { address: 'auto', name: 'auto' }` to the session create call.\\n- Pass an `idempotencyKey` derived from `userId + priceId + a coarse time bucket` (e.g., 5-minute window) so two clicks within the bucket get the same session URL.\\n\\n### New webhook event\\n\\n- Subscribe to `invoice.payment_failed` on the live (and test/preview) endpoints. Handler dispatches a \\\"card failed\\\" email and logs. No DB write beyond `stripe_events`.\\n\\n### Renewal-reminders deletion (full)\\n\\nDelete: `src/app/api/cron/renewal-reminders/route.ts` (+ `.test.ts`), `src/emails/RenewalReminderEmail.tsx` (+ `.test.tsx` + snapshot), `src/lib/mail/sendRenewalReminder.tsx`, the `crons` array in `vercel.json`. Leave the `renewal_reminder_sent` column on `app.subscriptions` (sibling repo's call to drop later — harmless for now).\\n\\n### Commit ordering inside the PR\\n\\nSingle PR, but bisectable commits in this order: (1) Prisma scaffolding + introspection, (2) repository modules + `getDb()` call-site replacement, (3) delete postgres client + renewal-reminders, (4) Stripe correctness fixes, (5) Stripe polish items. Each commit type-checks and the test suite passes.\\n\\n## Testing Decisions\\n\\n### What makes a good test here\\n\\nTests assert observable behavior: \\\"given event X, the row in `app.subscriptions` has these fields and exactly one welcome email was dispatched.\\\" Tests do not assert that a specific Prisma method was called with a specific argument shape — that's coupling to implementation. Behavior-level assertions survive future refactors of the repository modules.\\n\\nNote on **types ≠ tests**: Prisma's generated client gives compile-time type safety on query inputs and return shapes, which catches schema/code drift. It does not catch behavior bugs (was the right row updated? was the email sent exactly once? does the race fix actually prevent duplicate Stripe customers?). Tests are still required for behavior.\\n\\n### Strategy\\n\\nMocked unit tests, same speed and pattern as today, just mocking Prisma (or — preferred — mocking the new repository modules) instead of `getDb()`. Prior art: `src/lib/stripe/customer.test.ts`, `src/lib/stripe/events/handle.test.ts`, `src/app/api/stripe/webhook/route.test.ts`. Follow those.\\n\\n### Modules that get tested\\n\\n- **Subscriptions repository** — claim semantics (winner/loser), promote-or-insert correctness, idempotency of repeated calls.\\n- **Stripe-events repository** — record-if-new returns false on duplicates, mark-processed only updates rows where `processed_at IS NULL`.\\n- **Webhook handler** — runs on success, leaves `processed_at` null on handler failure, doesn't double-process on retried delivery.\\n- **Checkout session creation** — passes the right `customer_update` and idempotency key.\\n- **`getOrCreateCustomer`** — winner branch and loser branch both return the same customer ID; Stripe is called exactly once across two concurrent calls.\\n\\n## Out of Scope\\n\\n- Real-DB integration tests (deferred to a follow-up issue).\\n- Restricted API keys (follow-up).\\n- `automatic_tax`, `allow_promotion_codes`, `{CHECKOUT_SESSION_ID}` in `success_url` (nice-to-haves).\\n- Renewal reminders rebuild (deleted in this PRD; rebuilt in a future feature PRD).\\n- Dropping the now-unused `renewal_reminder_sent` column from `app.subscriptions` (sibling repo's call when convenient).\\n- Logic changes to `app.profiles` reads/writes — they're included in the Prisma model but only the SQL strings get replaced, no behavior change.\\n- Connect, Treasury, anything outside the subscription billing path.\\n\\n## Further Notes\\n\\n- **Operational rollout for Phase B**: do not create the live-mode webhook endpoint until both new sibling-repo migrations have been applied to the live DB. Order matters; live webhooks against an un-migrated DB would error.\\n- The Stripe API version pin is now `2026-04-22.dahlia` in `src/lib/stripe/client.ts` (handled in a prior PR). The new live webhook uses `2026-03-25.dahlia` — same codename, shape-compatible.\\n- **Preview testing path**: after the PR is up, the Vercel preview gets the new env vars (`DATABASE_URL` = pooler, `DIRECT_URL` = direct), Prisma generates against the introspected schema, and a Stripe test-mode webhook pointed at the preview URL exercises the full webhook + idempotency + race fixes end-to-end before live cutover.\\n- **Why one PR, not two**: per scoping decision, the Stripe fixes ride the Prisma foundation rather than shipping first. Slowest path to live, cleanest history.\\n\",\"comments\":[{\"id\":\"IC_kwDOR5LoTc8AAAABAqP0-A\",\"author\":{\"login\":\"luiscipparrone1\"},\"authorAssociation\":\"MEMBER\",\"body\":\"## Heads-up — Prisma 7 affects this PRD's Phase A & B specifications\\n\\n#35 (Prisma scaffolding) just landed on `preview`. While doing it I hit several breaking changes in Prisma 7 that ripple into the rest of this PRD's child issues. Flagging here so the spec stays consistent.\\n\\nWe're on **Prisma `7.8.0`** (latest stable). It introduced breaking changes vs Prisma 6 that affect every reference to \\\"the Prisma client\\\" in this PRD.\\n\\n### What changed in Prisma 7\\n\\n1. **`datasource db { url = env(...), directUrl = env(...) }` is gone.** The `url` and `directUrl` fields on the schema's datasource block are no longer supported. Connection URLs live in `prisma.config.ts` for the CLI, and runtime connections require a driver adapter. The acceptance criterion in #35 quoting the old syntax is no longer valid.\\n\\n2. **Runtime client requires a driver adapter.** No more `new PrismaClient()` with env-driven connection. Pattern:\\n    ```ts\\n    import { PrismaPg } from \\\"@prisma/adapter-pg\\\"\\n    import { PrismaClient } from \\\"@prisma/client\\\"\\n\\n    const adapter = new PrismaPg({ connectionString: process.env.DATABASE_URL! })\\n    export const prisma = new PrismaClient({ adapter })\\n    ```\\n   This matters for #38 (DB-layer migration) and the repository modules described in this PRD's \\\"Modules to extract\\\" section — they'll all instantiate via the adapter pattern.\\n\\n3. **`findFirst({ take })` is restricted to `1` or `-1`.** Use `findMany({ take: 0 })` for any \\\"does the connection work\\\" smoke check. Affects how tests in #38 / #39 are written.\\n\\n4. **Multi-file schema (`prisma/schema/` folder) is GA.** Used in #35 to keep Supabase's 480-line `auth` schema mirror separate from our 4 owned models. Re-introspection preserves the layout.\\n\\n### What changed about our schema state\\n\\n5. **`subscriptions` is currently `@@ignore`d in the generated client.** Prisma's introspection auto-marks the model because the table has no primary key / unique constraint. Means: `prisma.subscriptions.*` does not exist until #37 ships the `UNIQUE(user_id)` migration and we re-pull.\\n\\n   **Sequencing implication for #38**: the DB-layer migration cannot replace `getDb()` calls that touch `app.subscriptions` until **after** #37 lands and is re-introspected. Either #37 lands first, or #38's commit ordering (per this PRD) needs an explicit \\\"re-introspect after the migration\\\" step inserted before any subscription-related repository module is wired up.\\n\\n6. **`auth.users` cross-schema FKs require `auth` in `schemas`.** Even though we don't write or read auth models via Prisma, `app.pro_trials → auth.users` (and the FKs from `profiles`, `stripe_events`, `subscriptions`) force `auth` into `schemas = [\\\"app\\\", \\\"auth\\\"]`. Every auth model in `prisma/schema/auth.prisma` carries `@@ignore` so the generated client stays clean. The PRD's \\\"auth schema is Supabase-managed and stays out of `schema.prisma`\\\" is approximately preserved — auth models exist for FK validity but are excluded from the generated client.\\n\\n### ⚠️ Vercel deployment gotcha\\n\\nSupabase's transaction pooler (port `6543`, pgBouncer transaction mode) strips prepared statements, which Prisma's introspection / migrate engine relies on. **`DIRECT_URL` must point at port `5432`** (session pooler, or true direct — Vercel has IPv6 so `db.<ref>.supabase.co:5432` works). If `DIRECT_URL` is set to port `6543` on Vercel, `prisma generate` at build time will hang silently.\\n\\nSame warning posted on the affected child issues.\",\"createdAt\":\"2026-04-28T21:37:18Z\",\"includesCreatedEdit\":false,\"isMinimized\":false,\"minimizedReason\":\"\",\"reactionGroups\":[],\"url\":\"https://github.com/synergyio1/locus-landing-page/issues/34#issuecomment-4339266808\",\"viewerDidAuthor\":true}],\"labels\":[{\"id\":\"LA_kwDOR5LoTc8AAAAChKITNg\",\"name\":\"prisma\",\"description\":\"Prisma migration / DB layer work\",\"color\":\"2D3748\"}],\"number\":34,\"state\":\"OPEN\",\"title\":\"Migrate DB layer to Prisma + ship Stripe pre-launch correctness fixes\"}","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01JH2Y84FAsGQDjxDtbfAngj","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_0196e8hbr1uquykzrJw4HhYG","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"gh issue view 24 --json number,title,state,body,labels","description":"View issue #24 details"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":591,"cache_read_input_tokens":39824,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":591},"output_tokens":46,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"998550bb-d4bb-414a-8904-b08cbc843847","uuid":"9b98864b-2c2f-4d11-b4b7-45145ccc71eb"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01BXvemaJtPbkHNeqQ4zQ7iC","type":"tool_result","content":"{\"body\":\"## Problem Statement\\n\\nToday, clicking **Get Pro** on the pricing card sends users to `/download`, regardless of whether they're signed in. There's no signal that an account is required to subscribe, no path back to a logged-in state, and no way to manage an existing subscription from the marketing surface. The site nav is identical for everyone — a logged-in Pro subscriber sees the same generic \\\"Download\\\" CTA as a first-time visitor.\\n\\nThe user-perspective problem: *\\\"I clicked Get Pro and ended up on a download page. I have no idea if I have an account, no idea how to manage my subscription, and no obvious way to actually buy Pro from this page.\\\"*\\n\\n## Solution\\n\\nMirror Raycast's pattern:\\n\\n- Clicking **Get Pro** while logged out redirects to `/login` with a \\\"Please sign in\\\" notice. After auth, the user is returned to the same pricing surface they came from. A second click — now authenticated — fires Stripe checkout.\\n- Clicking **Get Pro** while logged in fires Stripe checkout immediately, using the cadence currently selected in the pricing toggle.\\n- The site nav becomes auth-aware. Logged-out users see the existing \\\"Download\\\" CTA. Logged-in users see an avatar (initials on a Cobalt circle) that opens a small dropdown with **Account** and **Log out**.\\n\\n## User Stories\\n\\n1. As a logged-out visitor, I want clicking **Get Pro** to take me to a sign-in page, so that I understand a Locus account is required to subscribe.\\n2. As a logged-out visitor redirected to login, I want a clear \\\"Please sign in\\\" notice on the page, so that I understand why I was redirected rather than just landing on a sign-in form unexpectedly.\\n3. As a logged-out visitor who clicked **Get Pro** from the homepage section, I want to return to the homepage pricing section after I sign in, so that I can continue from where I left off without hunting for the button again.\\n4. As a logged-out visitor who clicked **Get Pro** from `/pricing`, I want to return to `/pricing` after sign-in, so that the context I came from is preserved.\\n5. As a newly authenticated user back on the pricing page, I want to click **Get Pro** a second time and be taken directly to Stripe Checkout, so that I can complete my subscription.\\n6. As a logged-in user, I want clicking **Get Pro** to immediately start Stripe Checkout without a login detour, so that I'm not bounced through unnecessary screens.\\n7. As a user who toggled to **Yearly** pricing, I want **Get Pro** to start checkout for the yearly plan, so that the cadence I selected is honored.\\n8. As a user who toggled to **Monthly** pricing, I want **Get Pro** to start checkout for the monthly plan, so that the cadence I selected is honored.\\n9. As a user clicking **Get Pro**, I want immediate visual feedback that something is happening, so that I don't double-click or wonder if the button worked.\\n10. As a user clicking **Get Pro** when something fails, I want a readable inline error message, so that I know to retry rather than silently being stuck.\\n11. As a logged-in user on any page of the site, I want to see an avatar in the nav indicating I'm signed in, so that I can recognize my session state at a glance.\\n12. As a logged-in user, I want my avatar to show initials derived from my email, so that I have a consistent personal marker without needing to upload a profile picture.\\n13. As a logged-in user, I want clicking my avatar to reveal a small menu with **Account** and **Log out**, so that I can reach those actions from anywhere on the site.\\n14. As a logged-in user, I want **Account** in the dropdown to take me to `/account`, so that I can edit profile details and manage my subscription.\\n15. As a logged-in Pro subscriber on `/account`, I want to manage my subscription via the existing Stripe portal flow, so that cancellation and billing changes happen in one familiar place.\\n16. As a logged-in user, I want **Log out** in the dropdown to sign me out, so that I don't need to navigate to `/account` first to end my session.\\n17. As a keyboard user, I want the avatar dropdown to be operable via Enter/Space to open and Esc to close, so that the nav is usable without a pointer.\\n18. As a keyboard user, I want focus to move into the dropdown when it opens and return to the avatar when it closes, so that my focus position is predictable.\\n19. As a user who clicks outside the open dropdown, I want it to close, so that it doesn't linger on screen.\\n20. As a mobile user, I want the logged-in **Account** and **Log out** items to appear in the existing mobile sheet, so that I have parity with desktop.\\n21. As a logged-out visitor on mobile, I want the nav to behave exactly as it does today, so that nothing about the existing experience regresses.\\n22. As a returning user who logs out, I want the nav to reflect the signed-out state on the next navigation, so that the UI is honest about my session.\\n23. As a free-plan user looking at the **Free** column, I want its CTA to remain \\\"Download for macOS\\\", so that the auth gate only applies to the paid tier.\\n24. As a developer maintaining this code, I want the checkout-start logic to live in a single shared helper used by both `UpgradeButtons` and the pricing CTA, so that changes don't drift between two copies.\\n25. As a developer maintaining this code, I want pure helpers (initials, next-URL building) covered by unit tests, so that edge cases don't quietly regress.\\n\\n## Implementation Decisions\\n\\n**Auth-gated pricing CTA**\\n- Server pages (`/`, `/pricing`) call `createServerClient().auth.getUser()` and pass `isAuthed: boolean` down through the `Pricing` section to the Pro plan card.\\n- The Pro CTA becomes a small client component that branches on `isAuthed`:\\n  - Logged out → renders an anchor to `/login?next={pathname+hash}&notice=signin`.\\n  - Logged in → renders a button that calls the shared `startCheckout` helper with the currently selected cadence.\\n- The Free plan CTA is unchanged.\\n- The `next` URL is captured at click time from `window.location.pathname + window.location.hash` so homepage clicks return to `/#pricing` and `/pricing` clicks return to `/pricing`. Sanitization is done by the existing `sanitizeNext` on the login page (rejects external URLs and protocol-relative paths).\\n- After login, the user lands back on the pricing surface and must click **Get Pro** a second time. There is no auto-fire post-login.\\n\\n**Login notice**\\n- `LoginPage` accepts a new `notice` query parameter, distinct from `error`.\\n- A new non-error banner renders above the form when `notice=signin`, with copy \\\"Please sign in to continue.\\\"\\n- Unknown `notice` values are ignored (no banner).\\n- `error` styling and behavior are unchanged.\\n\\n**Shared checkout helper**\\n- A pure async function `startCheckout(plan)` returns a discriminated result union covering: ok, `price_not_configured`, malformed response, network failure, non-2xx HTTP. On success it assigns `window.location.href` to the Stripe URL.\\n- Both the new pricing `GetProButton` and the existing account `UpgradeButtons` call this helper. `UpgradeButtons` is refactored with no behavior change.\\n\\n**Auth-aware site nav**\\n- `SiteNav` is split into a server shell that fetches `{ email } | null` from Supabase and a client component (`SiteNavClient`) that owns all existing motion/state.\\n- Logged-out branch is identical to today (Download button + mobile sheet).\\n- Logged-in branch replaces the desktop **Download** button with an avatar button that opens a dropdown.\\n- Avatar shows two-letter initials derived from the email local-part on a solid Cobalt background with white text. No image fetch, no Gravatar.\\n- Dropdown contains **Account** (link to `/account`) and **Log out** (calls a shared sign-out server action). No \\\"Manage subscription\\\" item — `/account` already surfaces it contextually for Pro users.\\n- Dropdown supports click-to-open, Esc to close, click-outside to close, and focus trap while open.\\n- Mobile sheet appends **Account** and **Log out** items below the existing nav links when authenticated; otherwise unchanged.\\n- Auth state refresh is per-navigation (server-rendered). There is no client-side Supabase subscription on the nav. Logout already triggers a redirect, so post-logout the nav re-renders correctly.\\n\\n**Sign-out reuse**\\n- The sign-out behavior currently in the account `SignOutButton` is extracted into a shared server action so both the account page button and the new nav dropdown call the same code path.\\n\\n**Pure helpers (deep modules)**\\n- `startCheckout(plan)` — described above.\\n- `initialsFromEmail(email)` — deterministic two-letter result from email local-part. Handles single-character locals, missing separators, and non-ASCII gracefully.\\n- `buildLoginNext(pathname, hash)` — composes the `next` query value used by the pricing CTA. Output passes the existing `sanitizeNext` rules.\\n\\n**No new routes**\\n- No `/checkout/start`, no `/pro/start`. Post-login destination is just the pricing surface (`/#pricing` or `/pricing`).\\n\\n## Testing Decisions\\n\\nA good test asserts external behavior — what a user or caller observes — not internal implementation. Tests should survive a refactor that preserves behavior. Prior art:\\n- Pure-function unit tests live alongside `derive.ts` and `formatTrialDateLine.ts` under `src/lib/account/`.\\n- Page/component tests with mocked Supabase live in `src/app/account/page.test.tsx` and `src/app/login/page.test.tsx`.\\n- Route handler tests live in `src/app/api/checkout/create/route.test.ts`.\\n\\nModules to be tested:\\n- **`startCheckout`** — mocked `fetch`. Covers: success redirects to Stripe URL; `price_not_configured` body returns the matching reason; malformed JSON; rejected promise (network); non-2xx HTTP.\\n- **`initialsFromEmail`** — table of cases: standard `first.last@`, single-token local, single-character local, dot/underscore separators, non-ASCII characters.\\n- **`buildLoginNext`** — homepage with hash, `/pricing` with no hash, paths with query strings, malformed inputs. Output must round-trip through `sanitizeNext`.\\n- **`LoginPage`** — renders the `notice=signin` banner; does not render banner for unknown notice values; existing `error` rendering unchanged.\\n- **`Pricing` (Pro CTA)** — renders an anchor to `/login?...&notice=signin` when `isAuthed=false`; renders a button when `isAuthed=true`; Free plan CTA unchanged in both cases.\\n- **`SiteNav`** — logged-in branch renders an avatar with the expected initials and exposes Account + Log out actions; logged-out branch matches existing snapshot/behavior.\\n\\nExplicitly not tested:\\n- Dropdown open/close mechanics (DOM/focus interactions, low ROI relative to brittleness).\\n- `GetProButton` pending/error UI rendering (covered transitively by `startCheckout` tests + a render test in the `Pricing` suite).\\n\\n## Out of Scope\\n\\n- Avatar image upload or Gravatar integration.\\n- Account profile editing UI beyond what already exists on `/account`.\\n- A separate \\\"Manage subscription\\\" entry in the nav dropdown.\\n- Auto-firing Stripe checkout immediately after login (user must click Get Pro a second time).\\n- Live (non-navigation) auth state updates in the nav via a client-side Supabase subscription.\\n- Any change to the Stripe checkout API route, the webhook handler, or the billing portal route.\\n- Any change to the Free plan CTA.\\n- Mobile redesign of the nav beyond appending the two new items to the existing sheet.\\n\\n## Further Notes\\n\\n- The cadence toggle state lives in the `Pricing` client component. The `GetProButton` reads the current cadence from the same component scope; no new state container is introduced.\\n- The `notice` parameter is intentionally separate from `error` so future notices (e.g. \\\"session expired\\\") can be added without overloading error semantics or styling.\\n- Sanitization for `next` is already implemented on the login page; no duplicate sanitizer is added on the calling side. The CTA is permitted to construct any path-relative `next` and trust the login page to reject unsafe values.\",\"labels\":[],\"number\":29,\"state\":\"OPEN\",\"title\":\"Auth-gated Get Pro flow + logged-in nav state\"}","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"998550bb-d4bb-414a-8904-b08cbc843847","uuid":"0c452656-986e-43d8-b1a1-fd6ac6c79475","timestamp":"2026-04-28T22:25:28.989Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"{\"body\":\"## Problem Statement\\n\\nToday, clicking **Get Pro** on the pricing card sends users to `/download`, regardless of whether they're signed in. There's no signal that an account is required to subscribe, no path back to a logged-in state, and no way to manage an existing subscription from the marketing surface. The site nav is identical for everyone — a logged-in Pro subscriber sees the same generic \\\"Download\\\" CTA as a first-time visitor.\\n\\nThe user-perspective problem: *\\\"I clicked Get Pro and ended up on a download page. I have no idea if I have an account, no idea how to manage my subscription, and no obvious way to actually buy Pro from this page.\\\"*\\n\\n## Solution\\n\\nMirror Raycast's pattern:\\n\\n- Clicking **Get Pro** while logged out redirects to `/login` with a \\\"Please sign in\\\" notice. After auth, the user is returned to the same pricing surface they came from. A second click — now authenticated — fires Stripe checkout.\\n- Clicking **Get Pro** while logged in fires Stripe checkout immediately, using the cadence currently selected in the pricing toggle.\\n- The site nav becomes auth-aware. Logged-out users see the existing \\\"Download\\\" CTA. Logged-in users see an avatar (initials on a Cobalt circle) that opens a small dropdown with **Account** and **Log out**.