{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0196e8hbr1uquykzrJw4HhYG","type":"tool_result","content":"{\"body\":\"## Parent PRD\\n\\n#3\\n\\n## Problem Statement\\n\\nA user clicked \\\"Start 7-day Pro trial\\\" from `/account` and landed on a page that:\\n\\n1. Shows a **Pro** chip (solid accent color), with no indication this is a trial.\\n2. Shows no expiry date — the user has no idea when the trial ends.\\n3. Shows a **Manage subscription** button. Clicking it errors with *\\\"We couldn't find a subscription for your account. Please contact support.\\\"* — because there is no Stripe customer behind a free trial.\\n\\nFrom the user's perspective, the account page is lying (\\\"you're Pro!\\\") and then immediately contradicting itself (\\\"…but support can't find your subscription\\\"). Trust drops on the page that's supposed to confirm a successful action.\\n\\n## Solution\\n\\nThe `/account` page renders a **Trial** chip (softer accent-subtle tone) with a date line reading e.g. *\\\"3 days left · expires April 30, 2026\\\"*. The Manage subscription button does not appear during a trial — instead, the standard upgrade buttons (Monthly / Yearly) are shown to drive trial→paid conversion. A trial-aware welcome banner — *\\\"You're on Pro for the next 7 days. Make it count.\\\"* — confirms the trial just started. When the trial expires, the chip flips to **Free** with the existing \\\"Trial used on `<date>`\\\" disabled state.\\n\\nArchitecturally: the `entitlements_v` SQL view is correct as designed (binary entitlement gate, `'free' | 'pro'`). The bug is in the derive layer, which collapses the view's `plan` directly into the UI's display plan, discarding the `source` and `active_until` columns the view already exposes. The fix re-introduces a tri-state *display* plan computed from those columns, while the entitlement gate remains binary.\\n\\n## User Stories\\n\\n1. As a user who just clicked \\\"Start 7-day Pro trial\\\", I want a clear confirmation that my trial is active, so that I trust the action succeeded.\\n2. As a trial user, I want my account page to call my plan \\\"Trial\\\" rather than \\\"Pro\\\", so that I'm not confused about whether I'm being charged.\\n3. As a trial user, I want to see how many days are left in my trial, so that I can decide when to upgrade.\\n4. As a trial user, I want to see the exact calendar date my trial expires, so that I can put it on my calendar.\\n5. As a trial user, I want to see clear \\\"Upgrade to Pro\\\" buttons (Monthly and Yearly), so that I can convert before my trial ends.\\n6. As a trial user, I do NOT want to see a \\\"Manage subscription\\\" button, because I have no subscription to manage and clicking it produces a confusing error.\\n7. As a paid Pro user, I still want to see the \\\"Manage subscription\\\" button and a renewal/cancellation date, so that I can manage my Stripe subscription.\\n8. As a Free user who has never used my trial, I still want to see \\\"Start 7-day Pro trial — Free for 7 days, no card needed\\\", so that I can start my trial.\\n9. As a Free user who has consumed my trial, I still want to see \\\"Trial used on `<date>`\\\" disabled state, so that I understand why I cannot start another trial.\\n10. As a user whose trial just expired (and who didn't upgrade), I want my account page to show the Free state with \\\"Trial used on `<date>`\\\", so that the page reflects my current entitlement.\\n11. As a user who upgraded to a paid subscription mid-trial, I want my account page to show the Pro state with the *later* of (trial expiry, subscription renewal) as the active-until date, so that the date doesn't lie about when my access ends.\\n12. As a user landing on `/account?welcome=trial`, I want to see a celebratory banner in the Coach voice, so that the trial start feels intentional rather than silent.\\n13. As a user landing on `/account?welcome=1` (paid Pro), I still want to see the existing \\\"Welcome to Pro\\\" banner with the latency disclaimer, so that the paid welcome flow is unaffected.\\n14. As a user who left the `/account` tab open across midnight UTC, I accept that the \\\"X days left\\\" countdown can be stale by up to ~24h until I refresh, so that we don't ship timezone-fragile client refresh logic.\\n15. As an engineer maintaining feature gates, I want the entitlement plan (`free | pro`) to remain binary in the SQL view, so that every `plan === 'pro'` check across the app continues to work without modification.\\n16. As an engineer reading `deriveAccountView`, I want the trial-display logic to be a pure function of the snapshot, so that I can unit-test all branches without spinning up a database.\\n\\n## Implementation Decisions\\n\\n**Data layer**\\n\\n- `loadAccountSnapshot` extends its `entitlements_v` query to also select `source` (`'subscription' | 'trial' | null`) and `active_until` (timestamptz). These columns already exist on the view and encode the tie-break logic when both a paid subscription and a trial overlap.\\n- The `AccountSnapshot.entitlement` type gains the two new fields. Other consumers of `entitlements_v` (e.g. Fastify API) are unaffected because the view itself is unchanged.\\n\\n**SQL view (unchanged)**\\n\\n- `app.entitlements_v` continues to return `plan` as binary `'free' | 'pro'`. It is the entitlement gate for feature access. Changing it to return `'trial'` would silently break every `plan === 'pro'` feature check across the codebase.\\n\\n**Derive layer (deep module)**\\n\\n- `deriveAccountView` becomes a pure function of `(AccountSnapshot, now: Date)`, returning `AccountView` with a `displayPlan: 'free' | 'trial' | 'pro'` field.\\n- Mapping rules:\\n  - `displayPlan = 'pro'` when `entitlement.plan === 'pro'` and `source === 'subscription'`.\\n  - `displayPlan = 'trial'` when `entitlement.plan === 'pro'` and `source === 'trial'`.\\n  - `displayPlan = 'free'` otherwise.\\n- A new helper `formatTrialDateLine(activeUntil, now)` produces the date line for trials. Day-granular via `Math.ceil((activeUntil - now) / 86_400_000)`. Output format: `\\\"3 days left · expires April 30, 2026\\\"`. Edge cases: `\\\"Trial expires today\\\"` on day 0; `\\\"1 day left · expires …\\\"` (singular) on day 1.\\n- `primaryCta` returns `'Manage subscription'` only when `displayPlan === 'pro'`. For `displayPlan === 'trial'` or `'free'`, the page renders `<UpgradeButtons />`.\\n- Existing \\\"cancel_at\\\" / \\\"Renews on\\\" / \\\"Trial used on\\\" branches remain intact.\\n\\n**UI layer**\\n\\n- `AccountPage` branches on `view.displayPlan` instead of the raw entitlement plan.\\n  - `pro` → `<ManageSubscriptionButton />`\\n  - `trial` or `free` → `<UpgradeButtons />`\\n  - `<StartTrialButton />` renders only when `displayPlan === 'free'` and no `proTrial` row exists. The disabled \\\"Trial used on `<date>`\\\" state continues to render when a `proTrial` row exists for a `free` user.\\n- The plan chip uses the existing `Trial` tone (`bg-[var(--accent-subtle)] text-[var(--accent-text)]`) — already defined, no new styling.\\n\\n**Welcome banner**\\n\\n- The `?welcome` search param accepts two values: `'1'` (paid Pro, existing banner copy and latency disclaimer — unchanged) and `'trial'` (new copy: *\\\"You're on Pro for the next 7 days. Make it count.\\\"* — no latency disclaimer because the `pro_trials` insert is synchronous).\\n- `StartTrialButton` calls `router.replace('/account?welcome=trial')` on a `started: true` response. On `started: false` (already used), it continues to call `router.refresh()` so the disabled \\\"Trial used\\\" state appears.\\n- Paid-Pro `?welcome=1` flow is untouched.\\n\\n**Defensive code retained**\\n\\n- `ManageSubscriptionButton`'s `no_customer` error branch is kept. With the new gating, it is unreachable from a normal trial flow, but it remains a defense-in-depth path for the rare data-drift case where `app.subscriptions` has a row but the Stripe customer no longer exists.\\n\\n## Testing Decisions\\n\\nTests verify external behavior (rendered output, returned view shape, redirect target), not implementation details (no spying on internal helpers, no testing private state).\\n\\n**New: `derive.test.ts`**\\n\\nPure unit tests against `deriveAccountView`:\\n\\n- Free user, no trial consumed → `displayPlan: 'free'`, `trialCta.kind: 'start'`.\\n- Free user, consumed trial → `displayPlan: 'free'`, `trialCta.kind: 'used'` with started_at date.\\n- Active trial (entitlement `pro` + source `trial`) → `displayPlan: 'trial'`, dateLine matches `/X day(s) left · expires .../` or `/expires today/`, primaryCta is *not* \\\"Manage subscription\\\".\\n- Active subscription (entitlement `pro` + source `subscription`) → `displayPlan: 'pro'`, dateLine matches `/Renews on .../`.\\n- Cancelling subscription → dateLine `/Pro until .../` (existing branch preserved).\\n- Trial+subscription overlap, subscription wins (later active_until) → `displayPlan: 'pro'`.\\n- Trial+subscription overlap, trial wins → `displayPlan: 'trial'`.\\n\\n**New: `formatTrialDateLine.test.ts`**\\n\\nBoundary tests for the date-line formatter:\\n\\n- `now == activeUntil` → `\\\"Trial expires today\\\"`.\\n- `activeUntil − now` between 0 and 24h → `\\\"Trial expires today\\\"` (Math.ceil keeps it at 0 days).\\n- Exactly 24h difference → `\\\"1 day left · expires …\\\"` (singular).\\n- 3 days and a few hours → `\\\"4 days left · expires …\\\"` (Math.ceil rounds up).\\n- Verifies the expires date is rendered in `en-US` `month: long, day: numeric, year: numeric` UTC format (matching the existing `formatDate` helper).\\n\\n**Update: `page.test.tsx`**\\n\\n- Fix the broken trial test at line 112 — the existing mock uses `entitlement.plan: 'trial'`, which the real SQL view never produces. Replace with realistic snapshot: `entitlement.plan: 'pro', source: 'trial', active_until: <iso>`.\\n- Add a test for `?welcome=trial` rendering a banner with the trial copy and *not* the paid Pro copy.\\n- Add a test confirming `<ManageSubscriptionButton />` is *not* rendered for an active trial.\\n- Add a test confirming `<UpgradeButtons />` *is* rendered for an active trial.\\n\\n**Prior art**\\n\\n- `src/app/account/page.test.tsx` — same Vitest + Testing Library setup with mocked `loadAccountSnapshot` and `createServerClient`. New tests follow the same pattern.\\n- Pure-function tests for derivation logic don't yet exist for this module; the new `derive.test.ts` establishes that pattern.\\n\\n**Skipped tests**\\n\\n- `StartTrialButton` redirect target — one-line mechanical change; covered by the existing button tests if any, otherwise low ROI.\\n- `<UpgradeButtons />` rendering inside the trial branch — same component already tested for free users; the page-level test that confirms it renders for trial is sufficient.\\n\\n## Out of Scope\\n\\n- Changes to `app.entitlements_v` or any SQL migration. The view is correct as designed.\\n- Changes to the Fastify API or other downstream consumers of `entitlements_v`. They read `plan` and that contract is preserved.\\n- Re-design of the paid-Pro `?welcome=1` banner copy or its latency disclaimer.\\n- Real-time countdown / SSE / polling to refresh the \\\"X days left\\\" string while the tab is open. Day-granular precision with up-to-24h staleness on idle tabs is accepted.\\n- Trial reminder emails or trial-expiring nudges (handled separately by the renewal-reminder cron, #21).\\n- Changing the trial duration or eligibility rules.\\n- Stripe integration changes — the trial does not touch Stripe.\\n\\n## Further Notes\\n\\n- The existing `page.test.tsx` trial test has been green against an `entitlement.plan: 'trial'` mock that the production SQL view never produces. This is how the bug shipped without test failure. The fix includes correcting the mock to reflect the view's real output.\\n- The `entitlements_v` view encodes the trial-vs-subscription tie-break (lines 111-128 of `20260426000000_subscriptions_entitlements.sql`). Reading `source` and `active_until` from the view — rather than re-deriving from `subscription` and `proTrial` rows in TypeScript — avoids reproducing that tie-break logic on the client and risking drift.\\n- Watch for the singular/plural edge in the date line. `\\\"1 days left\\\"` would be a small but visible polish bug.\\n- The `Math.ceil` for day-granular countdown means: at the moment of the trial's first second, the user sees \\\"7 days left\\\"; at 6 days 1 second remaining, they see \\\"7 days left\\\" (still 7 by ceil); at exactly 6 days remaining, they see \\\"6 days left\\\". The user perception is \\\"the chip ticks down once per UTC day\\\", which matches the calendar-date the date line displays.\\n\",\"labels\":[{\"id\":\"LA_kwDOR5LoTc8AAAACgijXXA\",\"name\":\"realdeal-2026\",\"description\":\"Landing page and billing redesign — 2026\",\"color\":\"0E8A6B\"}],\"number\":24,\"state\":\"OPEN\",\"title\":\"[realdeal-2026] Trial display state on /account — fix Pro chip, hide Manage Subscription, add trial welcome\"}","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"998550bb-d4bb-414a-8904-b08cbc843847","uuid":"51c02526-9219-4663-a6e9-4b65eb43f9cf","timestamp":"2026-04-28T22:25:29.774Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"{\"body\":\"## Parent PRD\\n\\n#3\\n\\n## Problem Statement\\n\\nA user clicked \\\"Start 7-day Pro trial\\\" from `/account` and landed on a page that:\\n\\n1. Shows a **Pro** chip (solid accent color), with no indication this is a trial.\\n2. Shows no expiry date — the user has no idea when the trial ends.\\n3. Shows a **Manage subscription** button. Clicking it errors with *\\\"We couldn't find a subscription for your account. Please contact support.\\\"* — because there is no Stripe customer behind a free trial.\\n\\nFrom the user's perspective, the account page is lying (\\\"you're Pro!\\\") and then immediately contradicting itself (\\\"…but support can't find your subscription\\\"). Trust drops on the page that's supposed to confirm a successful 